In [3]:
#Quick example of how to make a plot from the ncdiag files

#load a file
fsr = ncd.obs('diags/x35_airswnd.diag_cris-fsr_n20_ges.20180530_00z.nc4')

#Set up the plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=1,ncols=1, figsize=(10,5))

#Plot longitude vs. latitude - you can ncdump the file to see the variable names.
#You can access the variables by the v() subroutine.  It returns a vector of the values
ax.scatter(fsr.v('Longitude'),fsr.v('Latitude'),marker='.',linewidth=0)
plt.show()

#Plot longitude vs. latitude - using short names
ax.scatter(fsr.v('lon'),fsr.v('lat'),marker='.',linewidth=0)

In [5]:
# So what's plotting above is actually all of the observations (all channels, 
# used or unused).  Let's set a mask and enable it to only look at one surface
# sensitive channel.

mask = '(ichan == 219) & (qcmark == 0)'
fsr.set_mask(mask)
fsr.use_mask(True)

#Set up the plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=1,ncols=1, figsize=(10,5))

#Plot longitude vs. latitude - using short names
ax.scatter(fsr.v('lon'),fsr.v('lat'),marker='.',linewidth=0)
plt.show()
In [6]:
# now lets color the dots by brightness temperature, for all obs:


# Range of brightness temperatures
tbmin=180
tbmax=330

mask = '(ichan == 219)'
fsr.set_mask(mask)
# I'm skipping the fsr.use_mask(True) because it is already set

#Set up the plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=1,ncols=1, figsize=(10,5))

#Plot longitude vs. latitude - using short names
ax.scatter(fsr.v('lon'),fsr.v('lat'),marker='.',c=fsr.v('obs'),vmin=tbmin,vmax=tbmax,linewidth=0)
ax.set_title('Channel 219 Brightness Temperature, All Obs')
plt.show()

# and only those that pass qc

mask = '(ichan == 219) & (qcmark == 0)' 
fsr.set_mask(mask)
# I'm skipping the fsr.use_mask(True) because it is already set

#Set up the plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=1,ncols=1, figsize=(10,5))

#Plot longitude vs. latitude - using short names
ax.scatter(fsr.v('lon'),fsr.v('lat'),marker='.',c=fsr.v('obs'),vmin=tbmin,vmax=tbmax,linewidth=0)
ax.set_title('Channel 219 Brightness Temperature, Used Obs')
plt.show()

# You can also use a template interface to open multiple files from
# multiple times.  
# Note, most times use the NCEP 'ndate' format:  YYYYMMDDHH

#fsr = ncd.obs('diags/x35_airswnd.diag_cris-fsr_n20_ges.20180530_00z.nc4')
startdate=2018053000
enddate=2018053018

fsr_tmpl = ncd.obs_template('diags/x35_airswnd.diag_cris-fsr_n20_ges.$yyyy$mm${dd}_${hh}z.nc4',startdate=startdate,enddate=enddate)

# Let's do the same brightness temperature plots, but for all data on 20 May 2018
# (aka from startdate to enddate in cell above):


# Range of brightness temperatures
tbmin=180
tbmax=330

# set mask
mask = '(ichan == 219)'
fsr_tmpl.set_mask(mask)
fsr_tmpl.use_mask(True)

#Set up the plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=1,ncols=1, figsize=(10,5))

#Plot longitude vs. latitude - using short names
ax.scatter(fsr_tmpl.v('lon'),fsr_tmpl.v('lat'),marker='.',c=fsr_tmpl.v('obs'),vmin=tbmin,vmax=tbmax,linewidth=0)
ax.set_title('Channel 219 Brightness Temperature, All Obs')
plt.show()

# and only those that pass qc

mask = '(ichan == 219) & (qcmark == 0)' 
fsr_tmpl.set_mask(mask)
# I'm skipping the fsr.use_mask(True) because it is already set

#Set up the plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=1,ncols=1, figsize=(10,5))

#Plot longitude vs. latitude - using short names
ax.scatter(fsr_tmpl.v('lon'),fsr_tmpl.v('lat'),marker='.',c=fsr_tmpl.v('obs'),vmin=tbmin,vmax=tbmax,linewidth=0)
ax.set_title('Channel 219 Brightness Temperature, Used Obs')
plt.show()
